{"status":200,"result":{"posts":[{"platformId":"11435528628_10159423992193629","platform":"Facebook","date":"2021-08-17 00:56:31","updated":"2021-12-28 10:15:03","type":"photo","message":"What a spectacular and mesmerizing day it was.. celebrating India's 75th Independence at the Hatch Cell, the iconic Boston landmark on Sunday with the rich color, vibrant traditions, and patriotic fervor. It was the celebration of freedom, democracy, unity, diversity and the values of people and their spirit, where our minds and hearts were decorated in tri-colors - joy and pride shared amongst all of us. It was perfect summer weather, with nice breezes from the Charles River. Also, in honor of Independence Day, the Boston City Hall Plaza was lit with tricolor from August 13 to 15th for 3 nights. Leading to the Hatch Shell celebration, IAGB held formal flag-raising ceremonies in over 50 towns, spreading the independence celebration across local towns and communities we live in. Live in concert by Berklee Indian Ensemble was a memorable one as the sounds of 'Vande Mataram vibrating through the Esplanade and the Charles River. Berkley’s music concert captured everyone’s spirit and patriotism - thousands in the crowd swayed and danced to the mesmerizing performance. . Also, IAGB recognized over 30+ organizations for their support and partnership with IAGB and community service & contributions during COVID 19 pandemic in the last 20+ months. This celebration was even more special as it was IAGB’s 35th India Day celebration at the Hatch Shell, which started in 1987 at the same location. Celebration of this scale wouldn’t be possible without support and participation from all corners. We would like to take this opportunity to thank: • Our sponsors - Pelmeds, AcceptU, ICC, Cuemath, New York Life Insurance, and over 30 exhibitions and advertisers. • Berklee Indian Ensemble and its founder Annette Philip for the fantastic live concert - magical voice and sounds with super energy and splendid musicianship • Talented choreographers, performers, musicians, and artists for the amazing and captivating cultural and band performances. • Over 30+ community organizations for their support, partnership, and being part of the celebration. • Food vendors - Maya Indian Bar & Grill, Home Kitchens and Mela restaurants for serving delicious Indian Cuisine throughout the day • Community Youth Excellence 2021 award winners - Arnav Bhakta, Sachi Badola, and Archita Neemlikanti • Sraveo for Photography and Videography and Fotu Duniya for Photography. • All the volunteers who joined us to pitch in for every effort all day long(Raghavendra Nanjaiah, Samhita Gowda, Angel Patel, Heny Patel, Sanchita Gowda, Esha Shinde, @Aditi Manjrekar, Kishan Angadi, Jayanth Angadi, Srinathan Gade, Anees Buxamusa, Swasti Bhargava, Shourya Gupta, Vasudha Kudrimoti, Dhriti Motwani etc) • Niren Chaudhary, CEO - Panera Bread for being our chief guest on this occasion. • DCR Hatch Shell staff and rangers for planning and managing the entire day operations so smoothly and efficiently. • Boston City Hall for lighting up the CHP with tricolor for three days. • MA state police for supervising and supporting the event, keeping everyone safe. • Our media partners - Lokvani, INE, MeraSangeet, and Boston city news outlets • TV Asia - Jharna Madan for covering the event. • 50+ towns (select board, mayor/council board, town administration) for flag-raising ceremonies. • Community members - DCR Hatch Shell estimated 7000+ community members who came to celebrate India's pride. IAGB team couldn’t thank you enough for the excitement, energy, and participation. I am extremely proud of my IAGB team - a dedicated, passionate, and dynamic team that kept the Community busy in the last two years with innumerable events and activities and memorable India Day and Republic Day cultural celebrations. Kudos to the entire EC team. We acknowledge that we are gathered on stolen land. We are on the traditional land of our ancestors who sacrificed their lives for our existence. ��The usual constitutional concept of racial equality, and the older concept of race as well as the evolving definitions, do not adequately encompass the political and legal status of American Indians. Uniquely, equality issues arise from the American Indian’s status as tribal sovereignty.��We are building a new ecosystem in the effort to bring “truth” to the American Indians. Organized religions often made significant efforts to destroy or take away the truth that the American Indian people already had and to demolish their cultural heritage. A better way would have been to take the time to see the truth and beauty existing within the cultures, the power, and healing that blessed the people through the ceremonies and medicines. It can be argued convincingly that, were it not for the strengthening ceremonies, medicines, and understandings, the American Indians would have been wiped out culturally.��We reverse centuries of inequities for American Indians in national civil rights, social injustice, and the struggles of American Indian communities. We need to amplify the stories, art, culture preservation, and historical accuracy as we reclaim our preservation and become advocates for our people and our land . . . . . . . . . . . .� Tribal Sovereignty is paramount. The U.S. Constitution recognizes Indian tribes as distinct governments and they have, with a few exceptions, the same powers as federal and state governments to regulate their internal affairs. Tribal Sovereignty includes the right to establish its form of government, determine membership requirements, enact legislation, and establish law enforcement, and court systems . . . . . . . . . . . . • Tribal Sovereignty refers to the right of American Indians and Alaska Natives to govern themselves.��• Racial session or equality for change in training and learning insight shows the root of racism on this land from Doctrine of Discovery and Manifest Destiny.��• Indian Country honors the seeds of this land, giving gratitude to Mother Earth for protecting its people with nutrients and natural resources for the past, present, and future generations. �• Mother Earth has been essential to the legacy. This is the land that we protect and fight for as it gives life with its teaching, growth, nourishment as we say Thank You. �. . . . . . . . . . .� Artist description of the Sovereignty-themed visual� About a thousand years ago, White Buffalo Calf Woman came to the ancestors of the Lakota, giving them a sacred pipe and a round rock. The rock, Black Elk said,��. . . is the Earth, your Grandmother, and Mother, and it is where you will live and increase. . . . All of this is sacred and so do not forget! Every dawn as it comes is a holy event, and every day is holy, for the light comes from your father Wakan-Tanka; and also you must always remember that the two-leggeds and all the other peoples who stand upon this earth are sacred and should be treated as such.� Black Elk, The Sacred Pipe + The Sacred halo around Sovereignty represents the sacredness, spirituality, and the importance of the right of self-government. �+ She is a Pipe Protector. The pipe is the power of spirituality to connect to the Creator. + She is a cultural preserver. + The antlers and mask represent her Clans. �+ Her bag of medicine and songs represents healing and reconciliation. + The red pipe bag represents prayers for the land, water, children, and adults of boarding schools of Canada and the United States.� + The drum is used to send prayers to the Creator for those who can’t speak for themselves. + The elderly hands holding the black blanket of wisdom are releasing the Hummingbirds for the souls to go home (MMIR and boarding school children). + The circles on the black blanket encompass soul and energy to use as strength from the ancestors as they speak to us. + The upper colored ++++ denotes the four directions. + Hand drums are used for prayers - prayers for healing. + Water is fluidity where rivers, streams, creeks are constant and are a very important element to the My cousins would tell me about how our great-great-grandfather, Cheii White, had originally farmed and raised sheep on the land our beloved merry-go-round stood. He acquiesced the land in order to build a school for the community so that our Diné could receive an education.\n\nI think about the sacrifice that my Cheii made to support our community, the government housing surrounding the school that my grandfather built, the decades of teaching that my grandmother and aunties invested into the bright minds of our Diné youth at that school. I think about how my grandmother ensured that nearly all her children attended the only college preparatory school on the reservation, Navajo Prep, over an hour away from our four corners community. I think about my auntie Phia who tirelessly worked for her PhD in Cancer Research at the University of Arizona, my cousin Kyii who has both the hands of an artist and the mind of an engineer, and my cousin Hia who will one day lead our people on the Navajo Nation as she begins law school this week. I think about my mother who will be pursuing her nursing degree this fall after prioritizing her children’s education first for so long.\n\nThe Diné singer Arlene Nofchissey’s renowned song, “Go My Son”, illustrates her desire for the Diné to pursue an education and bring their knowledge back to the people. Through the teachings of my family and my community, I arrived at my White Coat Ceremony equipped with blessings and a promise to give back to my community as they themselves have sang, blessed, worked, and sacrificed. I promise to use my knowledge and continued learning to mentor and support Indian Country as budding indigenous leaders also pursue higher education. I promise to investigate the issues targeting our communities and advocate for policy change. In coalition with the forces for change that compose the Association of Native American Medical Students board, I will help pave the way for Native American students into medicine as my family has done for me.\"\n\nShared from Association of Native American Medical Students Instagram What are you all planning to plant for Fall? Each winter, on average, your risk of frost is from December 6 through February 17. Almost certainly, however, you will receive frost from December 28 through January 23. You are almost guaranteed that you will not get frost from March 15 through November 14. Your frost-free growing season is around 292 days. Some notes on our summer : What appears done or has stalled in August : Japanese eggplant. Going strong : Various greens like Malabar spinach and gongura, okra, dosakaya, various gourds especially, now, such as ashgourd, bittergourd, snakegourd, various peppers. What never did well : Ridgegourd. Only one fruit so far :). What did okay : Bottlegourd, with about a large gourd or two a month. It required a lot of patience while I was waiting for the approval. Once you apply for the NIE, it is a test of your patience as you do not get any updates while you are waiting for the decision. However, I would request you to keep patience, if it is taking time, your chances of approval are high. I guess you will hear back rejections early than you thought. However, my understanding is that approvals are taking a lot of time. Anyways, I waited for over 3 weeks before I got my NIE approval. I travelled to Orlando via Dubai on my previously booked return flight. I had to leave my ticket open while I was waiting for the approval. Upon receiving the approval, I rebooked my flight with a price difference of approx $100.00 per person. At the Mumbai airport, I showed my RT-PCR test report (certified ICMR lab) with the NIE exception and a self attestation form from Emirates website. They rechecked all the documents one more time at the Dubai airport before boarding. When I landed in Orlando, the US immigration did not ask me any questions and I was out of the airport in about 30 mins after collecting my bags. Finally my kids are able to go to school from tomorrow, and I'm able to resume my office from tomorrow. Just have patience, and trust in your god. If your reasons in the NIE are genuine, you will get your approvals.
